---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Layout
  title="Dark Matter Context"
  description="The physics case for dark matter, axions, and why the DMRadio approach is well-motivated."
>

  <section class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Science Background</span>
      <h1>Dark Matter &amp; Axions</h1>
      <p class="desc">
        The evidence for dark matter is overwhelming. The question is: what is it made of?
        Axions and axion-like particles are among the best-motivated candidates, and DMRadio
        targets an unexplored corner of their parameter space.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Evidence for DM -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="two-col-60">
        <div>
          <span class="section-label">The Case for Dark Matter</span>
          <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">What Is Dark Matter?</h2>

          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            The first systematic evidence for missing mass came from galaxy clusters. In 1933, Fritz
            Zwicky applied the virial theorem to velocity dispersions measured in the Coma Cluster,
            inferring a total gravitational mass hundreds of times greater than the luminosity of its
            member galaxies could account for. He coined the term <em>dunkle Materie</em>&mdash;dark
            matter&mdash;to name the unseen component. Zwicky's contribution was foundational not
            merely for what he found, but for how he found it: by decoupling mass from light, he
            established the central method of all subsequent dark matter studies. Mass inferred from
            gravitational dynamics is independent of whether the source emits radiation, making dark
            matter detectable even before it is understood.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            The most direct kinematic evidence came from the rotation curves of spiral galaxies.
            Through the late 1960s and 1970s, Vera C. Rubin and W. Kent Ford measured how fast stars
            and gas orbit the centers of dozens of spiral galaxies at increasing distances from the
            core. If a galaxy's mass were concentrated in its bright stellar disk, orbital speeds
            should fall off with distance once you move beyond the visible stars&mdash;just as planets
            farther from the Sun move more slowly. Instead, Rubin and collaborators found that orbital
            speeds stay roughly constant out to the very edge of what could be measured, implying
            extended halos of invisible mass.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            Crucially, this result did more than add to the evidence for missing mass: it directly
            answered the skeptics of Zwicky's cluster work. One could always argue that Zwicky had
            simply miscounted the ordinary matter in the Coma Cluster&mdash;overlooked dim stars,
            cool gas, or dust. But Rubin's flat rotation curves continued well past the point where
            the stellar disk fades away entirely. Any uncounted ordinary matter would have to sit
            alongside the luminous matter; it could not explain gravity that keeps pulling on stars
            beyond the visible edge of the galaxy. The excess mass had to form an extended,
            invisible halo with no luminous counterpart whatsoever.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
            Later observations continued to reinforce these ideas. In particular, gravitational lensing
            made it possible to map mass directly from how gravity distorts the light of more distant
            background galaxies, and systems such as the Bullet Cluster
          </p>

          <!-- BULLET CLUSTER IMAGE — replace src with actual composite image -->
          <figure style="margin:0.25rem 0 1.25rem;">
            <div class="diagram-placeholder" style="aspect-ratio:16/9;">
              <p><strong>Bullet Cluster</strong></p>
              <p>Replace with Bullet Cluster composite image</p>
              <p style="font-size:0.8rem;">(Chandra X-ray + Hubble optical + weak-lensing mass map)</p>
            </div>
            <figcaption style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--gray-500);margin-top:0.6rem;line-height:1.5;">
              The Bullet Cluster (1E&nbsp;0657&minus;558): two galaxy clusters caught shortly after
              collision. The hot X-ray-emitting gas (pink; Chandra Observatory), which comprises most
              of the ordinary baryonic matter, has been slowed by electromagnetic interactions and
              displaced from the collisionless galaxies. The blue contours show the dominant mass
              concentration inferred from weak gravitational lensing&mdash;it coincides with the
              galaxies, not the gas. This spatial offset between ordinary matter and gravitational
              mass provides some of the most direct evidence that the bulk of matter is dark.
              <em>Image: X-ray: NASA/CXC/CfA/M.&nbsp;Markevitch et al.;
              Optical: NASA/STScI; Magellan/U. Arizona/D.&nbsp;Clowe et al.;
              Lensing map: NASA/STScI; ESO WFI; Magellan/U. Arizona/D.&nbsp;Clowe et al.</em>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            provided especially striking evidence because the hot X-ray-emitting gas, which contains
            most of the ordinary matter, is spatially separated from the dominant gravitating mass
            inferred from lensing. Together, these results established not merely that something is
            &ldquo;missing,&rdquo; but that most matter in the universe is nonluminous and revealed
            primarily through its gravitational effects. Dark matter is therefore a deeply established
            inference from astrophysical data, even though its microscopic identity has never been
            directly observed.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom:0;">
            Independent lines of evidence converge on the same conclusion. The acoustic peak structure
            of the cosmic microwave background (CMB), measured with precision by WMAP and Planck,
            encodes the relative densities of baryons, photons, and dark matter through their
            imprint on primordial sound waves. These data establish that dark matter constitutes
            roughly 26.8% of the total energy content of the Universe&mdash;approximately five times
            the baryon density&mdash;and that it must be cold and effectively collisionless to
            reproduce the observed peak heights and positions. Simulations of large-scale structure
            formation further show that the observed cosmic web of filaments, voids, and clusters
            could not have assembled in the available time without the gravitational scaffolding of
            a matter component that begins clustering before ordinary matter decouples from the
            photon bath (Bertone &amp; Hooper 2018).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1rem;">
          <!-- VERA RUBIN ROTATION CURVE PLOT — replace with actual figure -->
          <figure>
            <div class="diagram-placeholder" style="aspect-ratio:1;">
              <p><strong>Rubin, Ford &amp; Thonnard (1980)</strong></p>
              <p>Replace with rotation curve figure</p>
              <p style="font-size:0.8rem;margin-top:0.25rem;"><em>ApJ</em> 238, 471 &mdash; Fig.&nbsp;5</p>
              <p style="font-size:0.78rem;">Orbital velocity vs. radius for 21 Sc spirals</p>
            </div>
            <figcaption style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--gray-500);margin-top:0.6rem;line-height:1.5;text-align:center;">
              Rotation curves of 21 Sc spiral galaxies (Rubin, Ford &amp; Thonnard 1980). Each
              curve remains flat to the outermost measured radius, in contrast to the Keplerian
              decline expected if mass followed the luminous disk.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Axions -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">The Axion</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Why Axions?</h2>
      <div class="two-col">
        <div>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">The Strong CP Problem</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
            [Explain the strong CP problem in QCD: why the theta parameter appears in the QCD
            Lagrangian, why it should produce an observable neutron electric dipole moment (nEDM),
            and why the experimentally measured value is &lt;10<sup>&minus;10</sup> rather than O(1).
            This fine-tuning problem is unnatural in the Standard Model.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Peccei-Quinn mechanism: introducing a new U(1) symmetry broken at scale f<sub>a</sub>
            dynamically drives &theta; to zero. The pseudo-Nambu-Goldstone boson of this breaking
            is the axion, with mass m<sub>a</sub> ~ &Lambda;<sup>2</sup><sub>QCD</sub>/f<sub>a</sub>.]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Cosmological Production</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
            [Describe the misalignment mechanism for axion dark matter production. If f<sub>a</sub>
            is large enough, the axion can account for the observed dark matter abundance. The
            corresponding mass range is [X&ndash;Y] &mu;eV, overlapping with DMRadio's target band.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Also mention topological defect production (strings and domain walls) as an additional
            production mechanism, and how it extends the mass range where axions could be the
            dominant dark matter component.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Axion-photon coupling -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Detection Principle</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Axion-Photon Coupling</h2>
      <div class="two-col-60">
        <div>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            [Explain the axion-photon coupling g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub>. The axion couples to
            two photons through the Lagrangian term &frac14; g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub> a F&tilde;F.
            In the presence of a strong external magnetic field B<sub>0</sub>, this interaction
            allows axions to resonantly convert to photons when the axion mass matches the photon
            frequency: m<sub>a</sub>c<sup>2</sup> = &hbar;&omega;.]
          </p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            [Describe the expected signal power: P &prop; g<sup>2</sup><sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub>
            &rho;<sub>DM</sub> B<sup>2</sup><sub>0</sub> V Q / m<sub>a</sub>, where V is the effective
            volume and Q the quality factor. At DMRadio's target mass, this is an extraordinarily
            faint signal requiring quantum-limited detection.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [DFSZ and KSVZ benchmark models: these two canonical axion models predict specific values
            of g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub>. DMRadio aims to probe at or below these thresholds across
            its target mass range.]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <p><strong>Exclusion plot</strong></p>
            <p>g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub> vs m<sub>a</sub></p>
            <p style="font-size:0.8rem;margin-top:0.5rem;">Replace with sensitivity projection figure</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Landscape -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Experimental Landscape</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">DMRadio in Context</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;max-width:680px;">
        Multiple experiments are pursuing axion dark matter across complementary mass ranges.
        DMRadio targets the sub-&mu;eV window not accessible to cavity-based haloscopes like ADMX.
      </p>
      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">DMRadio (this experiment)</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Lumped-element solenoidal resonator. Target: [X&ndash;Y] &mu;eV. Quantum-limited SQUID readout.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag tag-blue">Sub-&mu;eV</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">ADMX</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Microwave cavity haloscope at University of Washington. Currently covering 2&ndash;40 &mu;eV.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">&mu;eV range</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">HAYSTAC</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Yale/Berkeley/Colorado experiment. Higher-frequency cavity search with squeezed-state receiver.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">10&ndash;100 &mu;eV</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">ABRACADABRA</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">MIT solenoidal broadband search; demonstrated detection principle used by DMRadio.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">Sub-&mu;eV</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">CASPEr</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">NMR-based axion search via axion-nucleon coupling. Complementary to photon-coupling searches.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">Ultra-low mass</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">SHAFT / AION</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Atom interferometry-based searches for ultralight dark matter and gravitational waves.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">Ultra-light</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-sm" style="background:var(--gray-50);border-top:1px solid var(--gray-200);">
    <div class="container" style="text-align:center;">
      <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Ready to go deeper?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;max-width:500px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;">
        Read our publications or explore how the experiment works in detail.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href={`${base}/experiment/`} class="btn btn-primary">The Experiment</a>
        <a href={`${base}/publications/`} class="btn btn-secondary">Publications</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
